      "---  ------          --------------  -----  \n",
      " 0   Temperature °C  1000 non-null   int64  \n",
      " 1   Mols KCL        1000 non-null   int64  \n",
      " 2   Size nm^3       1000 non-null   float64\n",
      "dtypes: float64(1), int64(2)\n",
      "memory usage: 23.6 KB\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Using pandas load the dataset (load remotely, not locally)\n",
    "science_data = pd.read_csv(\"science_data_large.csv\")\n",
    "# Output the first 15 rows of the data\n",
    "science_data.head(15)\n",
    "# Display a summary of the table information (number of datapoints, etc.)\n",
    "science_data.info()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Part 2. Splitting the dataset"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "785    2.518314e+03\n",
       "873    6.518410e+05\n",
       "65     8.230361e+05\n",
       "902    1.077368e+06\n",
       "317    2.069938e+05\n",
       "           ...     \n",
       "835    2.328286e+02\n",
       "192    4.957200e+05\n",
       "629    2.652735e+05\n",
       "559    1.104815e+06\n",
       "684    9.985940e+05\n",
       "Name: Size nm^3, Length: 900, dtype: float64"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 9,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Take the pandas dataset and split it into our features (X) and label (y)\n",
    "X = science_data[[\"Temperature °C\",\"Mols KCL\"]]\n",
    "y = science_data[\"Size nm^3\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Use sklearn to split the features and labels into a training/test set. (90% train, 10% test)\n",
    "X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.1, random_state=0)\n",
    "y_train"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Part 3. Perform a Linear Regression"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "/home/codespace/.local/lib/python3.12/site-packages/sklearn/base.py:493: UserWarning: X does not have valid feature names, but LinearRegression was fitted with feature names\n",
      "  warnings.warn(\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "array([ 863.58108791, 1006.12741921])"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 10,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Use sklearn to train a model on the training set\n",
    "model = LinearRegression()\n",
    "model_fit = model.fit(X=X_train, y=y_train)\n",
    "# predictions = model_fit.predict(X=X_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create a sample datapoint and predict the output of that sample with the trained model\n",
    "sample_point = [[690, 840]]\n",
    "model_fit.predict(X=sample_point)\n",
    "# Report on the score for that model, in your own words (markdown, not code) explain what the score means\n",
    "r_squared = model_fit.score(X=X_test, y=y_test)\n",
    "r_squared\n",
    "# Extract the coefficents and intercept from the model and write an equation for your h(x) using LaTeX\n",
    "model_fit.coef_"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "0.8761646752736476 is the score that I got for r_squared for the sample datapoint [690, 840]. We can thus say that the model predicts fairly well as the score is close to 1."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Sample equation: $\\hat{y} = \\hat{\\beta_0} + \\hat{\\beta_1}x \\implies \\hat{y} = 863.58 + 1006.13x$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Part 4. Use Cross Validation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "[0.82360363 0.84592328 0.80449234 0.88308699 0.87538513 0.87870759\n",
      " 0.86953137 0.8583128  0.83288207 0.84650312]\n",
      "0.85184283230004\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Use the cross_val_score function to repeat your experiment across many shuffles of the data\n",
    "scores = cross_val_score(estimator=LinearRegression(), X=X_train, y=y_train, scoring=\"r2\", cv=10)\n",
    "print(scores)\n",
    "print(scores.mean())\n",
    "# Report on their finding and their significance (done in markdown)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The average r-squared score across 10 folds is approximately 0.8518 after computing the average. This suggests that there is a somewhat strong relationship between the predictor and target variable, and thus the model can be considered reliable. In terms of variance, the scores range between 0.80449234 to 0.88308699, which indicates fairly consistent performance."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Part 5. Using Polynomial Regression"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "array([ 0.00000000e+00,  1.20000000e+01, -1.10383439e-07, -1.20916610e-11,\n",
       "        2.00000000e+00,  2.85714287e-02])"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 12,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Using the PolynomialFeatures library perform another regression on an augmented dataset of degree 2\n",
    "poly_model = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)\n",
    "transformed_data = poly_model.fit_transform(X=X_train)\n",
    "pd.DataFrame(transformed_data)\n",
    "\n",
    "model_fit = LinearRegression().fit(X=transformed_data, y=y_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "r_squared = model_fit.score(X=transformed_data, y=y_train)\n",
    "r_squared # returns 1.0\n",
    "model_fit.coef_\n",
    "# Report on the metrics and output the resultant equation as you did in Part 3."
   ]
  },
